FG-111 — Caption Discipline (Names • Capacities • Case No.)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A perfect caption prevents misrouting and “wrong case” excuses.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Standardize party names, capacities (official/individual), and case number; mirror it across brief, addendum, appendix, OA packet; file a caption-correction the moment it drifts.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 6-line caption-correction with one exhibit (judgment p.1).
	•	✅ Model Response: “Relief: correct to ‘Ryan-Touhill, in her official capacity’; basis: Judgment p.1; service updated; no schedule impact.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: One caption = one story everywhere.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A heading bar snapping into consistent labels.

⸻

FG-112 — Convert Emails to Paper (Memory, Not Inbox)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: If it matters, move it from email to the docket.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Summarize the exchange (dates/times), attach screenshots only as support, and file a Notice of Clerk Communication; cite rules; ask for a tiny order if a fix is needed.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line notice converting a scheduling email into the record with one ask.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Notice: clerk email 08/19 14:03; relief: set reply 09/22; exhibit A: thread; no argument change.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Inboxes vanish; dockets persist.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: An envelope icon arrowing into a stamped “FILED.”

⸻

FG-113 — Attachment Hygiene (PDF/A • Bookmarks • Title)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Clean files prevent “we couldn’t open it” problems.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Export searchable PDF/A, set Title metadata, add bookmarks mirrored to H2s, remove comments/layers; run a 5-item pre-upload checklist.
	•	📝 Assignment: Create a 5-line attachment checklist and paste it above your export button.
	•	✅ Model Response: “PDF/A ✓; Title ✓; bookmarks ✓; comments removed ✓; word cert ✓.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Hygiene earns credibility before page one.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A slim PDF with three green badges: Searchable • Bookmarks • Title.

⸻

FG-114 — “Not Reached” Spotlight (Make the Gap Visible)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Show where the court stopped—that’s your remand.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Quote the exact line (“did not reach harm”), pin it twice (Dkt/Tab), and map the missing findings; propose a 21-day instruction.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write a 6-line paragraph that turns a “not reached” note into a clean remand.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Order omits harm (Dkt 18:2; Tab 3 p.2) → remand 21 days for findings (a–d); 20-min harm hearing.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Absence is the strongest presence.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A bright highlighter over “not reached.”

⸻

FG-115 — Posture Footnote vs. Paragraph (Pick One)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Give just enough jurisdiction comfort.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: If posture is simple, use a footnote (“§1291; Rule 58 08/15; NOA 08/19”). If disputed, use a first-paragraph triangle (Statute • Clock • Copies).
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft both forms for your case and choose the shorter safe one.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Fn: §1291; Rule 58 08/15; NOA 08/19; Tabs 1–2.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Comfort without clutter.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A tiny triangle icon sitting in a footnote.

⸻

FG-116 — Two-Page Appendix Guide (Front Matter That Saves Hours)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A crisp guide turns staff into allies.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Page 1: Contents + hash lines; Page 2: Legend (Dkt/Ex/Tab), Crosswalk (Issue → Tab p.#), and Back-to-Brief note.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a two-page guide for your current appendix.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Legend: cites to PDF pages. Crosswalk: Harm → Tab 3 p.2; Timeline → Tab 5 p.1.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Navigation is persuasion’s twin.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two simple guide pages with a fingerprint footer.

⸻

FG-117 — OA Hand-Up Compliance (Policy-Clean)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Great hand-ups still fail if they break the rules.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Check chambers policy; mark “Hand-up” with case #; no new facts; hash the set; file a same-day notice with the packet as an exhibit.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write a 5-line compliance checklist for your OA packet.
	•	✅ Model Response: “No new facts; hashed; labeled; policy cite; notice filed same day.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Compliance keeps the focus on content.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small packet with a policy checkmark badge.

⸻

FG-118 — Parallel Forum Letter (Sequence, Not Drama)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Coordinated calendars prevent collisions.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: 1 paragraph: What’s pending where (dates/pins) + proposal: brief hold or limited remand with status; neutral tone.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line coordination letter for your matter.
	•	✅ Model Response: “State OA 09/10; federal appeal submitted. Proposal: hold 21d or remand 21d for findings; status day 14.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Sequencing reads as professionalism.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two timelines with a coordinating bracket.

⸻

FG-119 — Integrity Affidavit (Process Log = Proof)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Your log turns process into evidence.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Affidavit with date/time • action • artifact (receipt/screenshot) → attach to notices (delay, non-service, outage).
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 9-line affidavit template with three log entries.
	•	✅ Model Response: “07/31 09:42 — USPS receipt (Ex A:1); 08/02 — portal error 503 (Ex B).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Process is a fact pattern.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A lined log page with small receipt icons.

⸻

FG-120 — Escalation Map (Clerk → Supervisor → Chambers → Panel)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Escalate by ladder, not emotion.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Document attempts (date/time), then escalate one rung with a short, pinned ask; file a notice if the clock matters.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write your 4-rung escalation ladder for the current issue.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Intake (7/31 14:03) → Supervisor (8/01 09:20) → Chambers email (8/01 16:10) → Notice with order line.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Calm escalation builds leverage.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A four-step ladder with a small order card at the top.